hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider the frozen-coefficient, first-order in space and time linearization of a gauge-constrained subsystem that arises in numerical relativity when modeling gravitational wave spacetimes near Minkowski background. Let $u$ denote a representative physical field component and let $C$ denote its corresponding first-order reduction constraint, defined schematically by $C = w - \partial_{x} u$, where $w$ is an auxiliary field introduced to reduce second-order spatial derivatives to first order. To reduce the growth of violations of $C$, practitioners often add multiples of the constraints to the evolution equations (“constraint damping”). In a simplified model that captures the effect of injecting $-\kappa C$ directly into the principal part of the reduced system, assume the frozen-coefficient subsystem for $(u,C)$ in one spatial dimension is
$$
\partial_{t} \begin{pmatrix} u \\ C \end{pmatrix}
\;=\;
A^{x}(\kappa)\,\partial_{x} \begin{pmatrix} u \\ C \end{pmatrix}
\quad\text{with}\quad
A^{x}(\kappa) \;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
\kappa  \alpha \\
-\alpha  -\kappa
\end{pmatrix},
$$
where $\alpha0$ is a fixed coupling parameter determined by the background and choice of gauge reduction, and $\kappa\ge 0$ is the constraint damping strength. The principal symbol in the spatial covector direction $\xi\in\mathbb{R}$ is defined by $P(\xi;\kappa)=A^{x}(\kappa)\,\xi$. Strong hyperbolicity of the frozen-coefficient system requires that for every nonzero $\xi$ the principal symbol $P(\xi;\kappa)$ be diagonalizable over $\mathbb{C}$ with a complete set of eigenvectors.

Starting only from the above subsystem, the definition of the principal symbol, and the standard definitions of diagonalizability and Jordan decomposition, analyze the spectrum and eigenstructure of $P(\xi;\kappa)$. Determine the precise condition on $\kappa$ in terms of $\alpha$ under which the characteristic equation $\det\!\big(P(\xi;\kappa)-\lambda I\big)=0$ has a repeated eigenvalue with nontrivial Jordan blocks, i.e., the principal symbol is not diagonalizable. Express your final answer as a single closed-form analytic expression for the critical damping strength $\kappa$ that produces a nontrivial Jordan block. No numerical approximation is required.
